In <1992Mar9.163308.1905@info.ucl.ac.be> Meessen@slig.ucl.ac.be
(Christophe Meessen) writes:

>In article <1992Mar9.081248.14072@actrix.gen.nz>,
Kris.Heidenstrom@bbs.actrix.gen.nz writes:
>> The program has to be able to be run by the computer.
>> Therefore it is crack-able.

>Can you prove this assertion ?

Soitanly! :-)

Hook up a logic analyzer to the processor, run the program and dump
a cycle-by-cycle picture of what's happening to a (large) disk file.

In fact, some of the niftier logic analyzers have "personality
modules" for popular processors and automatically weed out the
important bus cycles and show you what instructions were executed in
assembly-language format.

